'''''Pontohedyle''''' is a [[genus]] of [[sea slug]]s, [[acochlidian]]s, a shell-less [[marine (ocean)|marine]] [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]]s in the family [[Microhedylidae]]. They are highly simplified and uniform slugs.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>

== Distribution ==
The genus ''Pontohedyle'' shows a [[circum-tropical]] distribution with a single derived species (Mediterranean/ Black Sea ''Pontohedyle milaschewitchii'') inhabiting [[temperate water]]s.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/> In the absence of a fossil record for meiofaunal slugs the only available estimate for divergence times derives from a [[molecular clock]] approach calibrated with shelled heterobranch fossils.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/> J<U+00F6>rger et al. (2010)<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2010">J<U+00F6>rger K. M., St<U+00F6>ger I., Kano Y., Fukuda H., Knebelsberger T. & Schr<U+00F6>dl M. (2010). "On the origin of Acochlidia and other enigmatic euthyneuran gastropods, with implications for the systematics of Heterobranchia". ''[[BMC Evolutionary Biology]]'' '''10''': 323. {{doi|10.1186/1471-2148-10-323}}.</ref> estimated the origin of the genus ''Pontohedyle'' to the [[late Cretaceous]], 84 mya (95% confidence interval ranging from 160<U+2013>60 mya), providing a rough estimation of how much time was available for diversification and circum-global dispersal of ''Pontohedyle'' slugs.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>

''Pontohedyle'' has never been found in colder waters despite a well-studied meiofauna and hydrographic conditions similar to the Mediterranean.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/> The distribution of ''Pontohedyle'' might be constrained by ancestry from warm-water adapted animals. <ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/> Considering the estimated mid to late Mesozoic origin and the recent primarily tropical distribution pattern in ''Pontohedyle'', it is most likely that this meiofaunal slug clade originated in [[Tethyan]] waters.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>

== Description ==
With its [[vermiform]] body, a putatively multi-functional radula, <U+2018>simplified<U+2019> organ systems and a special fast and imprecise mode of sperm transfer, ''Pontohedyle'' reflects a meiofaunal slug lineage highly adapted to its interstitial habitat.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>

''Pontohedyle'' is morphologically well-defined genus of [[meiofaunal]] slugs.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/> Specimens of ''Pontohedyle'' are externally uniform and easily distinguishable from other acochlids by the lack of [[rhinophores]] and the bow-shaped oral [[tentacle]]s.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/> ''Pontohedyle'' typically bear monaxone, rodlet-like spicules distributed randomly and frequently accumulated between the oral tentacles.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/> No diagnostic differences in external morphology or spicules could be detected between the collected populations apart from eyes externally visible or not.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/> Comparative [[Scanning electron microscope|SEM]]-examination of the available [[radula]]e revealed two types of the typically hook-shaped radula: a lateral tooth without a denticle (''Pontohedyle verrucosa'') or with a denticle (''Pontohedyle milaschewitchii'').<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>

''Pontohedyle'' slugs have a well-adapted body plan that can be conserved for millions of years in a worldwide evolutionary success story.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/> ''Pontohedyle'' presents a stunning example of extreme morphological stasis and uniformity over long evolutionary timeframes, probably constrained by their simplified bodyplan and by the requirements of the meiofaunal habitat.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>

== Species ==
The first discovered ''Pontohedyle'' species is well described and abundant ''[[Pontohedyle milaschewitchii]]'' from the Black Sea and Mediterranean.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/> The second discovered species is poorly known Western Pacific ''[[Pontohedyle verrucosa]]'' from the [[Solomon Islands]].<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/> In absence of distinguishing morphological characters J<U+00F6>rger et al. (2007)<ref>J<U+00F6>rger K. M., Neusser T. P. & Schr<U+00F6>dl M. (2007). "Re-description of a female ''Pontohedyle brasilensis'' (Rankin, 1979), a junior synonym of the Mediterranean ''P. milaschewitchii'' (Kowalevsky, 1901) (Acochlidia, Gastropoda)". ''[[Bonner Zoologische Beitr<U+00E4>ge]]'' '''55'''(3/4): 283-290. [http://www.zoologicalbulletin.de/BzB_Volumes/Volume_55_3_4/283_290_BZB55_3_4_J%C3%B6rger_Katharina_et_al.PDF PDF].</ref> synonymized the tropical Western Atlantic ''[[Pontohedyle brasilensis]]'' with its temperate congener ''Pontohedyle milaschewitchii''.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/> Subsequently (2012) authors tested [[molecular marker]]s to detect possible [[cryptic species]] and they reestablished ''Pontohedyle brasilensis'' as a valid taxon and they uncovered at least nine (undescribed) candidate species.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>

There are at least nine candidate species plus three confirmed valid species:<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>
* ''[[Pontohedyle brasilensis]]'' (Rankin, 1979)<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>
* ''[[Pontohedyle milaschewitchii]]'' (Kowalevsky, 1901)<ref name="Schr<U+00F6>dl 2010">Schr<U+00F6>dl M. & Neusser T. P. (2010). "Towards a phylogeny and evolution of Acochlidia (Mollusca: Gastropoda: Opisthobranchia)". ''[[Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society]]'' '''158''': 124-154. {{doi|10.1111/j.1096-3642.2009.00544.x}}.</ref><ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>
* ''[[Pontohedyle verrucosa]]'' (Challis, 1970)<ref name="Schr<U+00F6>dl 2010"/><ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>
* ''Pontohedyle'' sp. 1<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>
* ''Pontohedyle'' sp. 2<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>
* ''Pontohedyle'' sp. 3<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>
* ''Pontohedyle'' sp. 4<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>
* ''Pontohedyle'' sp. 5<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>
* ''Pontohedyle'' sp. 6<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>
* ''Pontohedyle'' sp. 7<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>
* ''Pontohedyle'' sp. 8<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>
* ''Pontohedyle'' sp. 9<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>

== Ecology ==
''Pontohedyle'' (and many other meiofauna taxa) are rare and can be expected to have small [[effective population size]]s.<ref name="J<U+00F6>rger 2012"/>

